      38 +## HTTP & requests                                                                                        
      39 +- An HTTP request is what your browser does every time you load a page.                                   
      40 +- requests.get(url) sends a GET request and returns a response object.                                    
      41 +- response.text is the raw content the server sent back.                                                  
      42 +- The User-Agent header tells the server what is making the request.                                      
      43 +  Default is "python-requests/x.x" which some servers block.                                              
      44 +  Setting it to a browser string (Mozilla/5.0) gets you through.                                          
      45 +                                                                                                          
      46 +## RSS                                                                                                    
      47 +- A standardized XML format news sites publish so programs can fetch articles.                            
      48 +- Alternative to scraping — the site gives you structured data directly.                                  
      49 +- Google News exposes RSS for any search query:                                                           
      50 +  https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=QUERY&hl=en-US&gl=US&ceid=US:en                                    
      51 +- Each item in the feed has a title, link, summary, and pubDate.                                          
      52 +                                                                                                          
      53 +## feedparser                                                                                             
      54 +- Parses raw RSS/XML into a clean Python object.                                                          
      55 +- feed.entries is a list of articles.                                                                     
      56 +- Each entry has .title, .summary, .link attributes.                                                      
      57 +- You can pass it a raw XML string: feedparser.parse(response.text)                                       
      58 +                                                                                                          
      59 +## Python data structures                                                                                 
      60 +- A list of dicts is the right structure for a collection of articles.                                    
      61 +- Each dict groups related fields together: {"title": ..., "link": ...}                                   
      62 +- entry.title.rsplit(' - ', 1)[0] strips the source name from the end of a title.                         
      63 +  rsplit splits from the right, 1 means split once, [0] takes the left part.                              
      64 +- re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', '', text) strips HTML tags from a string.                                            
      65 +  The pattern matches anything between < and >.                                                           
      66 +                                                                                                          
      67 +## Environment variables & secrets                                                                        
      68 +- Never hardcode credentials in your code.                                                                
      69 +- Store secrets in a .env file: KEY=value (no spaces, no quotes)                                          
      70 +- Add .env to .gitignore so it never gets committed.                                                      
      71 +- python-dotenv: load_dotenv() reads .env into environment variables.                                     
      72 +- os.getenv("KEY") retrieves the value by name.                                                           
      73 +- Anyone reading your code on GitHub sees variable names, not your real secrets.                          
      74 +                                                                                                          
      75 +## Email (SMTP)                                                                                           
      76 +- SMTP is the protocol email uses to send messages.                                                       
      77 +- Gmail's SMTP server: smtp.gmail.com, port 587                                                           
      78 +- You cannot use your real Gmail password programmatically.                                               
      79 +  You must generate an App Password:                                                                      
      80 +  Google Account > Security > 2-Step Verification > App Passwords                                         
      81 +- MIMEMultipart("alternative") creates the email envelope.                                                
      82 +  "alternative" allows both plain text and HTML versions.                                                 
      83 +- server.starttls() upgrades the connection to encrypted TLS.                                             
      84 +  Without it, your password travels over the network in plain text.                                       
      85 +- server.login(EMAIL, APP_PASSWORD) authenticates with Gmail.                                             
      86 +- server.sendmail(from, to, message) sends the email.                                                     
